<HEADLINE>
<P>
ORANGE COUNTY FOCUS: COUNTYWIDE; BUSINESS SETTLES SUIT OVER WEAPONS SALES 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By LESLIE BERKMAN 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 An Irvine business has agreed to stop selling belt buckle knives and "cane 
swords" and to pay $7,500 in costs and civil penalties in the wake of a 
consumer protection lawsuit filed against it by the Orange County district 
attorney's office, prosecutors said Friday. 
</P>
<P>
 Without admitting liability, the company, Ken Nolan Inc. and its president, 
William C. Warren, agreed to resolve the lawsuit that was filed Thursday, 
according to a statement released by the district attorney's office.The lawsuit 
contended that the sale of the items by Nolan violated state law prohibiting 
the sale of such concealed weapons. 
</P>
<P>
 Officials at the company could not be reached for comment Friday evening. 
</P>
<P>
 The lawsuit defined a belt buckle knife as a knife that is "made an integral 
part of a belt buckle and consists of a blade with a length of at least 2 1/2 
inches." A cane sword was defined as a "cane, swagger stick, stick, staff, rod, 
pole, umbrella or similar device having concealed within it a blade that may be 
used as a sword or stiletto." LESLIE BERKMAN 
</P>
</TEXT>
