<P>
ORANGE COUNTY FOCUS: FULLERTON; 7 APPOINTED TO PANEL OF FINANCIAL ADVISERS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By MIMI KO 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Seven residents have been appointed to serve on the newly created Financial 
Advisory Committee. 
</P>
<P>
 The committee will begin meeting twice a month to review the city's financial 
condition and make recommendations on how to balance the 1995-96 and 1996-97 
budgets, which are expected to face $2.1 million and $3.6 million deficits, 
respectively. 
</P>
<P>
 Committee members are: 
</P>
<P>
 * Arnold Miller, president of Technology Strategy Corp., chairman of the Cal 
State Fullerton Advisory Board and audit committee chairman of Merisel. 
</P>
<P>
 * Fred Mason, an attorney, member of the Cal State Fullerton Advisory Board 
and the Chamber of Commerce's 1994 "Man of the Year." 
</P>
<P>
 * Irvin C. Chapman, a former mayor whose father, Charles C. Chapman, was 
Fullerton's first mayor. 
</P>
<P>
 * John Young, a project engineer for Hughes Aircraft Co. 
</P>
<P>
 * Maynard M. Kambak, president of Kambak Consulting, a health care and 
retirement housing service. 
</P>
<P>
 * Raymond J. Gagnon, president and chief executive officer of Cerritos Valley 
Bank. 
</P>
<P>
 * James B. Lehey, president and chief operations officer of Sensotron Inc. 
</P>
<P>
 Alternate Steven G. Belasco, a self-employed marketing consultant, also was 
appointed to the committee. 
</P>
<P>
 Mayor A.B. (Buck) Catlin and Councilwoman Julie Sa interviewed about 15 
committee candidates and the city council made its final choice Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
 The committee is expected to come up with recommendations on the city budget 
for the council by January. MIMI KO 
</P>
</TEXT>
